==English==

===Etymology===
Equivalent to {{suffix|en|tight|en|id2=inchoative}}. From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|tyhtan}}, from the root of {{m|en|tight}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˈtaɪ.tən/}}
** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-tighten.wav|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|aɪtən}}
* {{homophones|en|titan|Titan}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To make [[tight]]er.
#: ''Please '''tighten''' that screw a quarter-turn.''
#* {{rfdatek|en|Fawkes}}
#*: Just where I please, with '''tightened''' rein / I'll urge thee round the dusty plain.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To become tighter.
#: ''That joint is '''tightening''' as the wood dries.''
# {{lb|en|economics}} To make money harder to borrow or obtain.
#: ''If the government doesn't '''tighten''' the money supply, inflation is certain to be harsh.''
# {{lb|en|economics}} To raise short-term interest rates.
#: ''The Fed is expected to '''tighten''' by a quarter-point.''

